    953: "Gravity is a fundamental force that explains the attraction between objects with mass. According to Newton's classical theory, every mass exerts an attractive force on every other mass, and the strength of this force depends on their masses and the distance between them. This interaction keeps planets in orbit around stars and governs the motion of celestial bodies. Einstein's theory of General Relativity further refined our understanding by describing gravity not as a force, but as a curvature of spacetime caused by mass. Massive objects, like planets and stars, warp the fabric of spacetime, and objects follow paths along this curvature. This explains why planets orbit stars and why light bends around massive objects, observed as gravitational lensing. Gravity influences the structure and behavior of the universe, from galaxies to atoms, playing a crucial role in forming structures like stars and planets and in the dynamics of the cosmos.",
    958: "Gravity is a fundamental force that attracts objects with mass toward each other. It is the reason why things fall to the ground and why planets orbit stars. On Earth, gravity gives weight to physical objects and causes the ocean tides. Isaac Newton first formulated the idea of gravity as a universal force, suggesting that every particle attracts every other particle. Albert Einstein later expanded this understanding with his theory of general relativity, which describes gravity as a curvature of space-time caused by mass. Essentially, massive objects like stars and planets warp the fabric of space-time, creating a \"well\" around them. Objects move along the curves in the well, which we perceive as the force of gravity. This explains why planets orbit stars and why light bends near massive objects. Though we can't see gravity, its effects are observable everywhere, shaping the universe's structure and behavior on both cosmic and everyday scales.",
    985: "Gravity is a fundamental force of nature that draws objects with mass towards each other. The most widely accepted theory explaining gravity is Albert Einstein's General Theory of Relativity. Before Einstein, Isaac Newton proposed that gravity was a force acting at a distance, causing objects to attract each other. However, Einstein revolutionized our understanding by proposing that gravity is not a force in the traditional sense. Instead, it is the result of the curvature of spacetime caused by the presence of mass. Massive objects like planets and stars create a dent in the fabric of spacetime, causing other objects to move along these curves. This is why planets orbit stars and objects fall towards the Earth. General Relativity also predicts phenomena such as gravitational waves and the bending of light around massive objects. Gravity is crucial for the structure and dynamics of the universe, influencing everything from the motion of galaxies to the behavior of light.",
    1010: "Gravity is a fundamental force of nature that attracts objects with mass towards each other. The concept has evolved over centuries, beginning with Isaac Newton, who described it as an invisible force pulling objects toward one another, explaining phenomena like why apples fall and planets orbit. Later, Albert Einstein revolutionized our understanding with his General Theory of Relativity, proposing that gravity isn't a force per se but a curvature in the fabric of space-time caused by massive objects. According to Einstein, objects follow paths through this curved space, which we perceive as gravitational attraction. This theory has been confirmed through various experiments and observations, such as the bending of light around massive bodies and the detection of gravitational waves, ripples in space-time caused by violent cosmic events. While Einstein's theory remains the best description we have, gravity is still an area of intense research, particularly in unifying it with quantum mechanics.",
